<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="358" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,678,1011,1074]" box="[151,393,1047,1074]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">
(
<figureCitation box="[159,237,1047,1074]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1104,1129]" captionTargetBox="[144,1444,181,1078]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[144,1444,181,1078]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Map showing the distribution of all the known Endroedyolini species with the type locality of Upsa centennial Deschodt, Sole &amp; Scholtz, new species in Alexandria forest. All the forests in South Africa (Mucina &amp; Rutherford 2006) are marked in green on the main map and major cities indicated with black circles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3625854" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3625854/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[251,320,1048,1074]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1911,1936]" captionTargetBox="[168,1421,530,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,517,1892]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype of Upsa centennial Deschodt, Sole &amp; Scholtz, new species (A, C, E–G) and Outenikwanus tomentosus Scholtz &amp; Howden, 1987 (B, D). A, B, habitus, dorsal view; C, D, line diagram of the meso- and metasternum; E, aedeagus, dorsal view; F, pygidium; G, labels. Scale bar = 1.0 mm for 2A–D and 0.5 mm for 2E, F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3625856" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3625856/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">2A, C</figureCitation>
, E–G)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,872,1115,1140]" box="[151,872,1115,1140]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">
Type-species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Deschodt, Sole &amp; Scholtz" authorityName="Deschodt, Sole &amp; Scholtz" authorityYear="2020" box="[296,733,1115,1140]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Upsa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="centennial" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[296,462,1116,1140]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Upsa centennial</emphasis>
Deschodt, Sole &amp; Scholtz
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[743,867,1115,1140]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1186,1861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,215,1186,1212]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Head</emphasis>
. Punctate with punctures small and close together; clypeus bidentate, denticles small, separated by approximately two times their length; antennae yellow; eyes not visible dorsally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1186,1861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,320,1258,1284]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Pronotum</emphasis>
. Strongly convex with lateral sides somewhat explanate; punctures small, irregularly spaced, two times further apart than their diameter and sometimes with short, recurved, associated setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1186,1861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,275,1330,1356]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Elytra</emphasis>
. Dark brown; short and sparse golden-brown recurved setae located in punctures; striae double grooved; elytra fused.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1186,1861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,303,1401,1428]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Sternum</emphasis>
. Mesosternum and metasternum fused, suture evenly round; mesosternum relatively wide medially with more than three irregular rows fitting in between coxae (
<figureCitation box="[841,929,1438,1464]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1911,1936]" captionTargetBox="[168,1421,530,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,517,1892]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype of Upsa centennial Deschodt, Sole &amp; Scholtz, new species (A, C, E–G) and Outenikwanus tomentosus Scholtz &amp; Howden, 1987 (B, D). A, B, habitus, dorsal view; C, D, line diagram of the meso- and metasternum; E, aedeagus, dorsal view; F, pygidium; G, labels. Scale bar = 1.0 mm for 2A–D and 0.5 mm for 2E, F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3625856" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3625856/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1186,1861]" box="[199,664,1473,1501]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1473,1500]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Pygidium</emphasis>
. Punctures indistinct (
<figureCitation box="[565,651,1474,1500]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1911,1936]" captionTargetBox="[168,1421,530,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,517,1892]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype of Upsa centennial Deschodt, Sole &amp; Scholtz, new species (A, C, E–G) and Outenikwanus tomentosus Scholtz &amp; Howden, 1987 (B, D). A, B, habitus, dorsal view; C, D, line diagram of the meso- and metasternum; E, aedeagus, dorsal view; F, pygidium; G, labels. Scale bar = 1.0 mm for 2A–D and 0.5 mm for 2E, F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3625856" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3625856/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Fig. 2F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1186,1861]" box="[199,1117,1509,1537]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,1509,1536]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Foretibia</emphasis>
. Narrow at base, gradually widening; three denticles on outside margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1186,1861]" box="[199,1000,1545,1573]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1545,1572]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Aedeagus</emphasis>
. Symmetrical, with parameres flattened terminally (
<figureCitation box="[900,987,1546,1572]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1911,1936]" captionTargetBox="[168,1421,530,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,517,1892]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype of Upsa centennial Deschodt, Sole &amp; Scholtz, new species (A, C, E–G) and Outenikwanus tomentosus Scholtz &amp; Howden, 1987 (B, D). A, B, habitus, dorsal view; C, D, line diagram of the meso- and metasternum; E, aedeagus, dorsal view; F, pygidium; G, labels. Scale bar = 1.0 mm for 2A–D and 0.5 mm for 2E, F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3625856" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3625856/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="358" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1186,1861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1582,1608]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Etymology</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Deschodt &amp; Sole &amp; Scholtz, 2020" authorityName="Deschodt &amp; Sole &amp; Scholtz" authorityYear="2020" box="[343,413,1582,1608]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Upsa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="new genus">UPSA</taxonomicName>
is the international coden (or acronym) for the University of Pretoria entomological collection (
<bibRefCitation author="Evenhuis, N. L." box="[222,396,1618,1644]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358" refId="ref3745" refString="Evenhuis, N. L. (2019) The insect and spider collections of the world website. Available from: http: // hbs. bishopmuseum. org / codens / (accessed 27 September 2019)" type="url" year="2019">Evenhuis 2019</bibRefCitation>
). The gender is masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="358" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1186,1861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1653,1680]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Distribution</emphasis>
. This monotypic genus is currently only known from the Alexandria forest in the 
<collectingRegion country="South Africa" name="Eastern Cape" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Eastern Cape Province</collectingRegion>
of 
<collectingCountry box="[288,431,1690,1716]" name="South Africa" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">South Africa</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[446,511,1690,1716]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1104,1129]" captionTargetBox="[144,1444,181,1078]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[144,1444,181,1078]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Map showing the distribution of all the known Endroedyolini species with the type locality of Upsa centennial Deschodt, Sole &amp; Scholtz, new species in Alexandria forest. All the forests in South Africa (Mucina &amp; Rutherford 2006) are marked in green on the main map and major cities indicated with black circles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3625854" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3625854/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="358" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1186,1861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1726,1752]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Remarks</emphasis>
. This genus looks superficially most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Scholtz &amp; Howden, 1987" authorityName="Scholtz &amp; Howden" authorityYear="1987" box="[840,1292,1726,1752]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Outenikwanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[840,1000,1726,1752]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Outenikwanus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Scholtz, C. H. &amp; Howden, H. F." box="[1008,1292,1726,1752]" pageId="1" pageNumber="358" pagination="75 - 119" refId="ref4042" refString="Scholtz, C. H. &amp; Howden, H. F. (1987) A revision of the southern African Ca [n] thonina (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Scarabaeinae). Journal of the Entomological Society of Southern Africa, 50, 75 - 119." type="journal article" year="1987">Scholtz &amp; Howden, 1987</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1308,1428,1726,1753]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1911,1936]" captionTargetBox="[168,1421,530,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,517,1892]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Holotype of Upsa centennial Deschodt, Sole &amp; Scholtz, new species (A, C, E–G) and Outenikwanus tomentosus Scholtz &amp; Howden, 1987 (B, D). A, B, habitus, dorsal view; C, D, line diagram of the meso- and metasternum; E, aedeagus, dorsal view; F, pygidium; G, labels. Scale bar = 1.0 mm for 2A–D and 0.5 mm for 2E, F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3625856" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3625856/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Fig. 2B, D</figureCitation>
) by virtue of the very wide medial separation between the metasternum and mesosternum. It can readily be separated, however, by having fewer setae and by the shape of the meso-and metasternal suture being evenly rounded whereas the suture of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scholtz &amp; Howden" authorityYear="1987" box="[298,458,1834,1860]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Outenikwanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[298,458,1834,1860]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="358">Outenikwanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is angulate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
